					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/theglyphstone" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1359260); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1359260&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610163352" alt="TheGlyphstone" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1359260)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/theglyphstone" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1359260); return false;" >TheGlyphstone</a></span> <span class="odate time_1351449551 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">28 Oct 2012 18:39</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1600145">
									

<p>I was considering writing up Mr. Shapey as an SCP to add to the series if this tale goes over well, but it doesn't make sense since he's so good at hiding and escaping from most things.</p>
<p>If you want the headcanon I was using when I wrote it, though, Shapey's problem is that his natural state is 'unshaped', a blobby mass of something-or-other. He can force himself to hold a stable form, but it hurts, and hurts worse the longer he maintains it, no more than a few minutes usually. Losing his hold on a shape where people can see him causes problems, and police like to shoot at horrific blob-monsters, he's got a bit of a phobia about them. So he spends most of his time hiding from the world, but gets to mingle with real people on nights like Halloween - it's easier to hold a shape when he's copying one rather than creating it from scratch then holding it.</p>
<p>The implication that he was shifting in view of people isn't intentional, though.</p>

							</div>

								
